## 4. Solid State Drive (SSD)

Solid State Drives (SSDs) are modern storage devices that store data using flash memory instead of mechanical components. Because there are no moving parts, SSDs provide faster data access and better reliability compared to traditional hard disk drives.

---

**Architecture and Operation**

An SSD consists of NAND flash memory chips, a controller, and firmware. Data is stored in memory cells as electrical charge, organised into pages and blocks.

When data is written, the controller updates the charge levels in these cells. When reading, it detects these charge differences and converts them into usable data. Since the process is fully electronic, access time is very low compared to disk-based storage.

The controller also performs important functions such as wear levelling, which distributes writes evenly across memory cells, garbage collection to clean unused data blocks, and error correction to maintain data integrity.

---

**Performance Characteristics**

SSDs provide high-speed read and write operations with very low latency. This improves overall system responsiveness, reduces boot time, and enables faster application loading. They also consume less power and are more resistant to physical damage.

The main limitation is cost, as SSDs are more expensive per gigabyte compared to HDDs. However, for most modern systems, the performance benefits make SSDs a preferred choice.

---

**Comparison with HDD**

| Feature        | HDD                         | SSD                          |
|----------------|-----------------------------|-------------------------------|
| Storage Type   | Magnetic disks              | Flash memory                  |
| Access Method  | Mechanical                  | Electronic                    |
| Speed          | Slower                      | Much faster                   |
| Durability     | Lower                       | Higher                        |
| Power Usage    | Higher                      | Lower                         |
| Cost per GB    | Lower                       | Higher                        |
